\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 The main screen is where you do most of your work. The hardest part is to find all the features \endash  be sure to right-click everything\'85
\par 
\par {\b Waveform}: The green waveform is a visual representation of the sound. It actually displays peak levels. On the waveform, you\rquote ll find two thin vertical lines, a red one and a white one. The red line is the {\i marker}
 position, while the white is the {\i cursor}. You can move the cursor by pressing the left or right arrow keys on the keyboard. Use CTRL or SHIFT keys to make it move faster or slower.
\par 
\par {\b Marker}: The marker (a red line) position is where a split will be added when you press the split button.
\par 
\par {\b Position}: Is where the cursor (playback, sound) currently is. Click this box with the mouse to change the display format like on a CD player (or right-click and select one of the four modes)
\par 
\par {\b Total time}: Is the number of minutes of audio currently \ldblquote checked\rdblquote  in the {\i track list}.
\par 
\par {\b Track list}: Displays the current tracks (splits). You can rename and delete them. If you change the name to \ldblquote blank\rdblquote , it will get a default name. Each track also has a checkbox. If the track is \ldblquote checked\rdblquote 
, it will be saved to disk. If unchecked, it will not be saved when selecting File-Save.
