\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 Let me start by telling that CD WAV is not a sound editor, even though it has the same \ldblquote look and feel\rdblquote 
. The differences are mainly in the way it is supposed to be used. The primary functions of CD WAV are record
ing WAV files and splitting huge WAV recordings into smaller tracks, whereas sound editors are usually designed to make modifications to the audio data itself.
\par 
\par Now why would I use CD WAV instead of [fill in your favorite sound editor]?
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1\fs20 \'b7\tab}\pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}A sound editor usually works with temporary files. This becomes very time consuming if the files are hundreds of megabytes.

\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1\fs20 \'b7\tab}CD WAV works in \ldblquote batch mode\rdblquote . Basically, you define the tasks to be completed (split into tracks), and when you\rquote re satisfied, you \ldblquote commit\rdblquote  these. 
A sound editor would apply each modification immediately.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1\fs20 \'b7\tab}CD WAV records directly into a WAV file on your harddisk. This saves both space and time. The Windows Sound recorder program even can\rquote t buffer to harddisk at all.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1\fs20 \'b7\tab}CD WAV always works in CD sectors. This ensures that tracks can be written to a disc in Disc-At-Once mode without clicks or unwanted pauses between tracks.
\par \pard \widctlpar Now I know there exist sound editors that can do some of these things, but try to find one that allows all of this in a simple way\'85
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \b\f5\fs28\kerning28 \page {\cs17\super ${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super $} Step by step}} {\cs17\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super #} bystep}} {
\cs17\super K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super K} step}} {\cs17\super +{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super +} steps}} Step by step
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 Basically, there are five steps in using CD WAV to put your favorite album on a CDR:
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs20 1?\tab}\pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta ?}}{\uldb Set up the analogue recording part}{\v setupaudio}
. This usually means connecting a tape deck or pick-up to your computer\rquote s sound card.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs20 2?\tab}{\uldb Determine good volume settings}{\v tune} and other adjustments for your recording.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs20 3?\tab}{\uldb Digitize the recording}{\v actualrecording}, typically by putting it on your harddisk.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs20 4?\tab}{\uldb Split the recording into songs}{\v splitfile}, one per WAV file.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs20 5?\tab}{\uldb Burn the CDR}{\v burn} from these WAV files. 
\par \pard \widctlpar Steps 1 and 5 are the only steps CDWAV won\rquote t do for you, but I can give some tips.
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \b\f5\fs28\kerning28 \page {\cs17\super ${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super $} Setting up your audio equipment}} {\cs17\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super 
#} setupaudio}} {\cs17\super K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super K} setup; audio; analogue}} {\cs17\super +{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super +} steps}}Setting up your audio equipment
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 
Everybody usually has different equipment. Some of you may own expensive profesional mixing and recording material, others will feel the home or portable HiFi set fills their needs. I cannot give complete information on every combination of audio and comp
uter equipment. Most people owning advanced equipment probably know what they\rquote re talking about anyway, and probably can teach me things. I\rquote ll stick to giving tips on how to get it working with your home set.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Quick setup
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 My all favorite way to set up a computer as audio recorder is as a tape deck. The audio card usually has both recording and playback connectors, so if your HiFi set has a tape connector (preferably two if you\rquote 
d want to keep using your regular set) use it. Connect the \lquote line out\rquote  (some soundcards only have \lquote speaker out\rquote  connectors, you\rquote ll have to dig into your manual to see if you can use those as line outputs too) to the 
\lquote play\rquote  or \lquote input\rquote  connectors on the audio set. Connect the recording output of the set to the line input of the soundcard. If you only ha
ve one external tape connector on your set, and you want to use both the computer and the tape deck connected to it, you can put them in \lquote series\rquote 
. The play output from the tape deck connects to the line-in of the soundcard, and the line out of the soundcard now goes into the input of the audio set\rquote 
s amplifier. This allows you to directly record from the tape deck, and still be able to use everything like you used to. The tape deck and computer can switch positions to allow playing tapes while the computer i
s turned off, and to simplify recording from other resources than the tape deck.
\par Note that connecting a pick-up directly to your  soundcard will not work, you need a phono pre-amplifier in between. Some, however, come with built-in pre-amplifiers, so you won\rquote 
t need to have one. Usually, the audio set will take care of it, so setting it up as a tape deck solves this issue.
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \b\f5\fs28\kerning28 \page {\cs17\super ${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super $} Tuning volume settings}} {\cs17\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super #} tune}}
 {\cs17\super K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super K} volume; tuning; settings; test mode}} {\cs17\super +{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super +} steps}}Tuning volume settings
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 
This is one of the most important steps in successful audio digitizing. To get a good signal-to-noise ratio, the volume should be as loud as possible. But to prevent clipping, the volume setting is limited. So the optimal setting is to have the sound just
 hit the clipping level. This is almost impossible to accomplish. In general, if your volume is above half the max level, you\rquote ll lose less than a single bit out of 16, or 6dB S/N of 98 total dB. 
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 A test mode recording
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 Press the record button (red circle) to show the {\uldb recording setting dialog}{\v IDH_RecSettings}. The first radio button gives you an option to run a \lquote test mode\rquote 
. This mode will do everything the audio recording would do, except that it will just throw away the sound data after processing, instead of writing it to disk. The other 
options, like voice-activation and auto-stop, function exactly the same as in a normal recording, so the test mode can also be used to test these settings. After pressing the start button, the soundcard inputs will be enabled and any input will be process
ed. On screen, you\rquote ll see the min and max levels reached during short 1/3 second intervals. Below the green waveform, you\rquote ll see three LEDs. The green LED indicates that the signal is above \lquote silence\rquote 
. If the audio level raises above the \lquote loud\rquote  level (usuall
y about 90%), the yellow LED will flash. The red LED will indicate that clipping has occurred, and the sound volume should be lowered. The red LED can be switched of again by clicking it. Each (horizontal) pixel in the waveform display will represent 1/3 
second of audio.
\par Note that the test mode recording only helps to calibrate volume levels and such. You cannot detect buffer overruns by this, because the critical part is writing the data to disk.
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \b\f5\fs28\kerning28 \page {\cs17\super ${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super $} Actual recording}} {\cs17\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super #}
 actualrecording}} {\cs17\super K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super K} recording; disk; actual; harddisk; buffer; overrun}} {\cs17\super +{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super +} steps}}Actual recording

\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 After connecting your equipment, and calibrating volume setting, you are ready to record your precious vinyl album or tape to the harddisk.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Harddisk recording
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 Press the record button. Switch the destination to file. You can type a filename, or use the browse button to point-and-shoot one. An estimate on available space is given directly below the filename.
\par You can use the other options too. The stop criteria are very handy when you won\rquote 
t be present during the recording. The recording can be stopped after a timeout (you probably know how long the recording will be) and/or a silence interval. Setting a silence stop criterion will stop the recording after the input goes silent for a
t least the given amount of seconds.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Buffer overrun
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 While doing CD recording, you\rquote ll probably came along the buffer underrun, the event causing sleepless nights and tons of coasters in CDR world. In harddisk recording, you can get a buffer overrun instead.
\par While recording to harddisk, CDWAV records into memory buffers, and writes these to harddisk, so they can be reused. Like most wav recording programs, CDWAV has a total buffer of about 4 seconds. If, for some reason, the data is being written to harddisk 
too slowly, the buffer will overrun, as more data is arriving from your soundcard, but the buffer is full, so the data is lost. The recording will have skips in it. To prevent this, CD WAV can run as a high or even real-time priority process. See the {
\uldb settings}{\v IDH_Settings} section.
\par To prevent overrun, your system needs to keep up a steady 174kB/s transfer to harddisk. A good 386-class machine can easily live up to these standards.
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \b\f5\fs28\kerning28 \page {\cs17\super ${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super $} Splitting the file}} {\cs17\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super #} splitfile}
} {\cs17\super K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super K} splitting; tracks; remove split; remove silence; save}} {\cs17\super +{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super +} steps}}Splitting the file
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 Next step in building your own live CD is splitting the recording into tracks or songs.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Let me help you
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 CD WAV has a built-in {\uldb auto-split}{\v IDH_AutoSplit} function. This will look for silent parts, and add a split poi
nt in the middle of that silence. If your recording has silences, this function will do most of the work for you. If the recording has no silence intervals, as is usually the case with real live recordings, you\rquote 
ll have to do it manually. Typically one will first run the auto-split, and add or remove some split points afterwards.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Do it yourself
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 The bottom part of the screen holds the split list. You can see what split points have been added, and the corresponding time intervals. To add a split point, find th
e part of the song where the split is. Use the playback controls and the full view to navigate in the recording and roughly locate the spot. Now click the mouse in the bar directly below this point. The zoomed part of the waveform will show this in 
\lquote sector\rquote  detail. Click in this window to place the split marker. Press the split button to add the split. The full wave and split list will reflect your changes.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Removing a split
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 To remove a split, select the split to delete in the list at the bottom. Right click on it to popup a small menu. Select the remove option to delete the split.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Cutting out silent parts or songs
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 
Sometime your recording will have excessively long silent parts in it. You can also cut these out. To do this, treat the silent part as a song. Add a split point at the beginning and end of the silent part (or just one if it\rquote 
s at the start or end of the recording).
\par Each split point has a check box in front of it. By unchecking this box, that part of the audio will not be saved to disk later. Uncheck the box for silent parts and songs you wish to leave out.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Saving
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 
The last part is to save the songs you just recorded. You can modify the filenames to be written by clicking on them like you would in explorer to rename a file. The default name is the name of the recorded wave with the split index as a two-digit number.

\par Press the save button, and select a location for the files. All splits with a checkmark in front of them will be saved in that location. These files will be ready to burn.
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \b\f5\fs28\kerning28 \page {\cs17\super ${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super $} Burn}} {\cs17\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super #} burn}} {\cs17\super K
{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super K} CDR; burn; write; recorder}} {\cs17\super +{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super +} steps}}Burn them
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 This is the part I can\rquote t do for you. You need a CD Recorder and appropriate software to do this. All software I know of will allow you to burn the WAV files to a CDR.
\par If you experience trouble with software claiming not to be able to read my WAV files, please contact {\ul the author of CD WAV}{\v authorpopup}, and tell him the complaint. None of Adaptec\rquote s CDR products had trouble with CD WAV.
\par Basically, if your system can record audio with CD WAV, your system is capable of running CDR software. I managed to burn flawlessly at 2x from a 486SX-33 (actually an overclocked 25 MHz) machine with a AVA1542 SCSI card and HP 6020 burner.
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \b\f5\fs28\kerning28 \page {\cs17\super ${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super $} Common questions}} {\cs17\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super #} faq}} {
\cs17\super K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super K} FAQ; Questions; Common questions}} Common questions
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Audio recording
\par \pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \f5 I can hear sound, but nothing is recorded and the LEDs don't light up
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 Most probable cause is the volume setting.
\par There should be a "speaker" icon next to your clock on the task bar. (If not, use Start/Programs/Accesoires/Multimedia/Volume). Double click it to pop up the mixer panel. Choose Options, Properties, and select "Recording" for "Adjust volume for". Then, ma
ke sure all the volume controls in the bottom box have been checked. Click OK. The panel now allows you to select recording volumes and sources. Make sure that "Line in" (or Auxiliary) is checked and used as only input. Now it should work.
\par \pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \f5 How can I adjust (raise/lower) input levels?
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 You'll have to do this with the mixer program for your soundcard. It is hiding under the speaker icon next to the clock (see the previous question).
\par \pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \f5 Recording produces occasional skips
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 There can be several causes for this. Let me name a few.
\par Most likely some problem in the soundcard driver. Make sure you have the latest drivers for your card. If you have a Creative card like the soundblaster 16 or any of the AWE series, use Microsoft's built-in drivers. They're better than the on
es Creative supplies. If this doesn't help, go to {\i File}, {\i Preferences}
 and set the slider labeled "Recording Mode" to the middle position. This solves the problem for some of the driver compatibility problems. You're getting buffer overruns. The help file explains what this is, and how you can solve it 
