\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Recording destination
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 Usually you\rquote ll want to record an audio file. Some sound editors never ask for a file at this point, but record into a temporary file (or, like the standard Windows sound recorder, into
 memory) and copy that data to disk if you press the Save button.
\par CD WAV always records directly into a (valid) WAV file. This saves both disk space and time. You have to type a filename or select one using the browse button next to the input box.
\par If you wish, you can do a test mode recording. Everything recorded in test mode is just thrown away. This is useful for tuning volume settings to avoid clipping.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Voice activated start
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 If you check this button, the recording will wait until the input rises above th
e silence level before starting to record to harddisk. The time display will start running as soon as the actual recording starts. Thanks to buffering, the recording will include a few sectors before the input raised above silence.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Silence is below
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 The automatic start and stop functions need this to determine whether the input is silent or not. If the sample\rquote 
s amplitude remains below this level, it will be considered silence. The number is a positive sample value. Samples range from -32768 to 32767. For exa
mple, setting this to 512 will trigger a voice activated start if a sample below -512 or above 512 has been detected. The green LED lights up during a recording.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Loud is above
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 Much like the silence level, the loud level determines what level is considered to be \ldblquote dangerously\rdblquote 
 loud. The only use is that the yellow LED will light up during recording if the input raises above this level.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Stop recording after ... minutes
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 If you are recording from some other media (like a tape or vinyl), you usually know the duration of the recording. Setting this field will stop the recording after the time elapses.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Stop recording after \'85 seconds silence
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 This is much like a voice activated start. If, after the recording started, the input goes silent for a period longer than this, the recording will stop. This is convenient if you want to record something while you\rquote 
re eating lunch or so.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Start recording at the following time
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 Use your computer like a VCR, and set the time at which you want the recording to start. You need to keep CD Wave running for this.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \b\f5\fs28\kerning28 \page {\cs17\super ${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super $} Auto split}} {\cs17\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super #} IDH_AutoSplit}} {
\cs17\super K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super K} auto; split}} Auto Split
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 Splitting up a WAV file into tracks can be a tedious and time-consuming task. CD WAV can help you split it up by detecting pauses between songs. This is usually the first thing to try after opening or recording a WAV file.

\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 How it works
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 CD WAV uses two criterions to determine where the pauses are: The silence level and the silence time. The {\ul silence level}{\v IDH_SilenceLevel}
 determines what music level is considered to be silence. The level is a sample value, ranging from 1 to 32767. Sample values can range from -32768 to 32767, if the absolute value of all samples is below the silence level, it is considered a silent part. 
If this silent part lasts longer than the {\ul silence time}{\v IDH_SilenceTime} criterion, the silent part is considered to be a pause, and a track split will be added in the silent section, at a {\ul relative position}{\v IDH_RelativeSplit}.
\par \page {\cs17\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super #} IDH_SilenceLevel}} {\b Silence level}
\par Samples range from -32768 to 32767. Perfect silence would be represented as al zeroes (appear on screen as a line in the center). In analogue recordings, you\rquote 
ll probably never see this. Thus you can specify an envelope around the zero value that is also considered \ldblquote silence\rdblquote . The meaning of this value is also shown as a percentage.
\par \page {\cs17\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super #} IDH_SilenceTime}} {\b Silence time for split}
\par Silences occur quite often in some music parts. To distinguish between \ldblquote in-song\rdblquote  and \ldblquote between-song\rdblquote  silence, a simple criterion is used. If the silent period lasts longer than this time interval, it\rquote 
s considered a split. If it\rquote s shorter, it\rquote s ignored.
\par \page {\cs17\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super #} IDH_RelativeSplit}} {\b Relative split position}
\par The relative split position is where you want the split to occur inside the silent period. If you set this to 100%, the split point is inserted at the beginning of the next song. If you set it to 0%, the split will be placed at the end of the preious song
. Do to the inaccuracy of the \ldblquote silence\rdblquote  detection, you\rquote ll probably not select any of these extremes, but more in the range of 20-80%
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \b\f5\fs28\kerning28 \page {\cs17\super ${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super $} Select output}} {\cs17\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super #}
 IDH_SelectOutput}} {\cs17\super K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs17\super K} save; file; output; convert; compress}} Select output
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 This dialog allows you to write out the individual tracks to disk.
\par 
\par First select a directory from the tree to the left of the screen. You can rename, delete and create directories from here. Be careful, pressing Enter here will accept all changes and start saving the files.
\par Keep an eye on the Space box where you can check how much room is left on the disk, and how much you\rquote ll need to save all selected tracks.
\par 
\par If you wish, you can also save the tracks in a different format than they were recorded. Just select another format, as in the {\uldb recording}{\v IDH_RecSettings} settings. You can also chose various compressed formats, to save diskspace.
\par 
\par {\b No conversion:} Saves the file in the same format as it was recorded. Usually the option that you want for recording to CD.
\par {\b WAV:} Allows you to select any WAV format. You can change the sample rate or number of bits, and also use the ACM (Audio Compression Manager) to save any format that your system has a codec for. The file will always be a WAV file.
\par {\b MP3:} Allows you to save files to MP3. You also need to install the LAME codec for this to work (see {\field{\*\fldinst ref  HYPERLINK http://www.cdwave.com/download.html {{\*\datafield 
