\ldblquote lossy\rdblquote  format, which means that the quality of the audio will degrade (a bit). 
You have a choice between several presets, average and constant bitrate encoding. The presets usually offer the best quality for a given source, variable bitrate is usually better quality than constant bitrate. The constant bitrate setting is mainly used 
for incompatible players like older hardware MP3 devices. Most devices will playback any format you choose here. The settings here correspond to using \ldblquote LAME --preset\ldblquote  on the commandline
\par {\b OGG Vorbis:} Save to OGG Vorbis format. This is a lossy compression, similar to MP3, but does not require any patented technology so the format is totally free (as in freedom). You can balance between larger file size and more quality.
\par {\b FLAC:}
 Free Lossless Audio Compression. Another free format, but this one is lossless, which means that the compressed file, when played or otherwise decompressed, hold all the original data and does not involve any quality loss. Any setting is of equal quality
, but higher compression will take longer to compute. This format is ideal for archiving. You can compress 8, 16 and 24 bit data, and any number of channels.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\widctlpar \b\i\f5 Tip
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20 Never use MP3 (or any other lossy compressed) format when you want to create a CD. The MP3 format is not \ldblquote gapless\rdblquote 
, and this will introduce clicks on track boundaries. When creating a CD, use only uncompressed WAV format for optimal quality.
